The two questions, however, ol Bacon’s influence during the past, and the value os his works to‘ the student at the present time, seem to be so distinct as to require separate treatment, however much they may run into each other.

The intrinsic value oi Bacon's logical works to the student at the present time, apart from their historical interest, as having, to adopt the fine saying os Macaulay, ‘moved the intellects which have moved the world,' may be briefly considered under two aspects. The first is their general effect in guarding, stimulating, and disciplining the intellect; the second is the amount of definite logical doctrine, comprised in them, which retains any permanent value.

With regard to the first point, I know no work ol the same kind so stimulating to a young render, or so likely to foster habits oi cautious and independent investigation, as the First Book ottho Novum Organum.
